***** ETCD Backup & Restore in Kubernetes – Simplified *****
ETCD is the brain of Kubernetes, storing all cluster data such as Pods, Deployments, Services, Secrets, ConfigMaps, and cluster configurations. A proper backup can save your cluster during disaster recovery.
📌 Step 1: Get ETCD Certificates

cat /etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml | grep etcd

📌 Step 2: Take ETCD Backup

ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot save /tmp/etcd-backup.db \
--cacert=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/ca.crt \
--cert=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.crt \
--key=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.key

📌 Step 3: Restore Snapshot

ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot restore /tmp/etcd-backup.db \
--data-dir=/var/lib/etcd-backup \
--cacert=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/ca.crt \
--cert=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.crt \
--key=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.key

📌 Step 4: Update ETCD Manifest
Edit:

vi /etc/kubernetes/manifests/etcd.yaml

Change:

path: /var/lib/etcd

To:

path: /var/lib/etcd-backup

📌 Step 5: Verify

kubectl get pods -n kube-system

💡 Easy Way to Remember:
Find Certs → Backup → Restore → Update etcd.yaml → Verify
🔑 TLS Flags:
--cacert = Trust ETCD Server
--cert = Client Identity
--key = Authentication Key
